          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-816690?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Verizon 面临着来自无线和有线竞争对手的激烈竞争。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Victor J. Blue/彭博新闻</p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001081843"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/drew-fitzgerald" itemprop="url" rel="author">德鲁·菲茨杰拉德</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">更新于 2023 年 7 月 25 日中午 12:47（美国东部时间） </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/verizon-vz-q2-earnings-report-2023-955fdc2e"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/VZ" class="company-name">Verizon Communications</a>表示，现在评估解决其网络最古老部分的铅护套电缆问题可能需要花费多少钱还为时过早，这个问题一直困扰着这家电信公司，因为该公司专注于发展无线业务。</p><p>财务主管托尼·斯基亚达斯周二对投资者表示：“这一领域存在许多未知因素，包括不受干扰的铅护套电缆是否会带来健康风险。” “我们认为没有一种有意义的方法来估计公司的任何潜在成本，或者任何此类估计都有用。”</p><p> 《华尔街日报》的一项调查发现， <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/lead-legacy-a266d59b?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">老化的铅包电话线</a>仍然在全国纵横交错，可能在某些地区造成潜在的健康危害。 <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/VZ" class="company-name">Verizon</a>表示，第三方专家正在测试《华尔街日报》报道中提到的其网站，但几周后才会有结果。</p><p> Verizon 表示，在其铜缆网络中不到 540,000 英里的电缆中，含铅电缆只占一小部分，不过该数字不包括从 MCI 和 XO Communications 购买的网络部件。斯基亚达斯表示，该公司仍在研究这些被收购公司的历史记录。</p><p> <a href="https://quotes.wsj.com/T">AT&amp;T</a>上周表示，其网络中 200 万英里的护套铜缆中，铅包层线路所占比例不到 10%。 <a href="https://quotes.wsj.com/T">AT&amp;T</a>首席执行官约翰·斯坦基 (John Stankey) 在给员工的一份说明中写道，“《华尔街日报》的报道与独立专家长期以来关于铅包层电信电缆的安全性和我们自己的环境测试的说法相冲突”，该公司将与利益相关者合作解决任何问题。新的安全问题。该公司定于周三公布第二季度业绩。</p><p>两家公司都继承了前身公司的老化电话线网络，但几乎所有利润都来自更现代的光纤和手机连接。</p><h3>无线引擎</h3><p>Verizon 在最近一个季度增加了更多主要无线客户，但报告利润和收入下降，这是客户<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/time-to-upgrade-your-old-phone-more-consumers-say-not-yet-11661079600?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">升级旧智能手机</a>所需时间更长的症状。</p><p>这家美国用户数量最多的手机运营商在 6 月份季度结束时，其后付费电话连接数增加了 8,000 个，其不断增长的业务部门继续抵消了消费者部门萎缩的影响。投资者跟踪后付费客户群以及预付费电话和家庭互联网订阅的变化，以衡量电信公司的财务状况。</p><p>来自无线和有线竞争对手的激烈竞争给威瑞森最近的稳定利润蒙上了阴影。在过去一年半的大部分时间里，其消费者部门的客户流失，促使该公司<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/verizon-shakes-up-executive-team-after-tough-year-f28cbbc3?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">重组了其最高管理层</a>，并<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/verizon-overhauls-mobile-plans-to-make-them-less-confusing-8ff1e790?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">彻底改革了无线计划的营销方式</a>。</p><p>第二季度总收入下降 3.5% 至 326 亿美元。</p><p> Verizon 表示，销量下滑主要是由于智能手机升级减少，随着用户使用设备的时间更长，这一趋势在整个行业持续存在。受无线家庭互联网增长、价格上涨和部分费用收入重新分类的推动，其核心无线服务收入增长 3.8%，达到 191 亿美元。</p><h3>底线</h3><p>Verizon 的整体利润从上年同期的 52 亿美元降至 46.5 亿美元。按每股计算，利润从 1.24 美元降至 1.10 美元，这一数字包括与裁员相关的遣散费以及其他费用。不包括一次性项目，利润强于分析师的预期。</p><p>首席执行官表示：“我们为改善运营绩效而采取的措施正在发挥作用，我们有信心实现全年的财务目标。”</p>卫翰思在新闻稿中说道。<p></p><h3>投资者反应</h3><p>Verizon 股价在周二交易中上涨约 1%。</p><p>由于收入增长疲弱和巨额债务负担令投资者感到不安，Verizon 及其竞争对手 AT&amp;T 的股价在过去一年中大幅下跌。随着美联储加息，派息股票也难以吸引投资者，此举催生了更多高收益投资争夺投资者的注意力。</p><p> 《华尔街日报》调查后，7 月份电信股进一步下跌。最近几天，市场已经复苏，因为这些公司提供了有关仍在其网络中的线路的一些详细信息，使华尔街分析师能够完善对潜在清理成本的估计。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/d90969df-db3f-4890-9f4e-2892f502493a.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p>写信给德鲁·菲茨杰拉德 ( <a href="mailto:andrew.fitzgerald@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">andrew.fitzgerald@wsj.com)</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 25 Jul 2023 16:47:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/verizon-vz-q2-earnings-report-2023-955fdc2e</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/verizon-vz-q2-earnings-report-2023-955fdc2e<author><![CDATA[Drew FitzGerald]]></author><category> WSJ公司</category><category>公司收益</category><category>电线/电缆</category><category>电信服务</category><category>无线电信服务</category><category>工业品</category><category>财务绩效</category><category>收益</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>威瑞森通讯公司</category><category>维兹</category><category>美国电话电报公司</category><category>时间</category><category>财务绩效</category><category>收益</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>电线</category><category>电缆</category><category>电信服务</category><category>无线电信服务</category><category>工业品</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Stuck on a Flight? Know Your Rights During a Tarmac Delay]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>如果恶劣天气或飞机拥堵导致您滞留在跑道上，以下是您作为航空公司乘客的权利<figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-821700/?width=2000&amp;size=1.5" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>乔恩·克劳斯 (Jon Krause) 的插图<span>乔恩·克劳斯 (Jon Krause) 的插图</span></figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001073822"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001073822"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者： <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/allison-pohle" itemprop="url" rel="author">艾莉森·波尔</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">更新于 2023 年 7 月 25 日中午 12:13（东部时间） </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/tarmac-delay-rights-airports-9c5b1464"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p>今年夏天，对于美国旅行者来说，计划外的停机坪时间变得令人沮丧地司空见惯。</p><p>有关停机坪延误的联邦数据滞后三个月，但经验丰富的旅客表示，他们观察到全国主要机场停机坪上的等待时间很长。在典型的停机坪延误中，飞机要么到达并需要等待登机口，要么在飞机舱门关闭后等待起飞。</p><p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/flight-cancellations-and-delays-mount-as-thunderstorms-hit-east-coast-c11c9161?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">恶劣的天气</a>给航空公司的运营带来了压力，并导致停机坪延误。天气问题导致飞机起飞延迟，并导致抵达飞机的可用登机口短缺。</p><p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/united-airlines-newark-flights-cut-9f5f57f6?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">纽约地区机场的</a>延误情况非常明显。运营机场的纽约和新泽西港务局表示，当天气恶化时，出发和到达的时间会更加间隔。航空公司高管还表示<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/faa-tries-to-ease-flight-congestion-at-new-york-airports-933d1da0?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">，空中交通管制员的短缺</a>加剧了挑战。</p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"></div><p> “没有人对机场延误感到高兴，这就是为什么我们正在与合作伙伴密切合作，以减少停机坪延误，而停机坪延误很大程度上是由纽约/新泽西地区和目的地机场最近的恶劣天气造成的。”港务局发言人在一封电子邮件中说道。</p><p>十多年前，交通部实施了一项禁止停机坪长时间延误的规定。如果航空公司让乘客在飞机上停留的时间超过交通部规定的时间且没有机会下机，他们可能会面临罚款。航空分析师表示，这一规定大大减少了乘客在飞机上滞留数小时的事件数量。但航班延误仍然时有发生——交通部对停机坪延误的<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/united-airlines-is-fined-1-9-million-for-runway-delays-11632516201?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">航空公司处以罚款</a>，其中包括 2021 年对<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/UAL" class="company-name">美国联合航空公司 (United Airlines)</a>的 190 万美元罚款。</p><p> 7月17日<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/DAL" class="company-name">，达美航空一架</a>从拉斯维加斯飞往亚特兰大的航班在地面上滞留了大约三个小时，而室外温度却高达110多度。</p><p> Tashina 和 Janssen Robinson 与他们 16 岁的侄女和 1 岁的婴儿一起乘坐飞机。住在亚特兰大的罗宾逊一家在家庭团聚后乘飞机回家，他们说飞机上的空调已经打开。但塔西娜说，微弱的气流感觉就像“在阳光下吹风扇”。</p><p>交通运输部正在调查这起事件。达美航空表示正在配合调查，并正在调查导致机上温度不舒服的原因。</p><p>交通部针对这些情况制定<a href="https://www.transportation.gov/individuals/aviation-consumer-protection/tarmac-delays" target="_blank" class="icon none">了消费者保护措施</a>，尽管这些保护措施可能有限。以下是关于停机坪延误期间您的权利的信息。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="444" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-822623?width=700&amp;height=444" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> DOT 规则要求航空公司在国内航班延误超过 3 小时、国际航班延误超过 4 小时之前开始转移到乘客可以离开的地方，但有一些例外。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Kena Betancur/Getty Images</p></figcaption></figure></div><h3>为什么飞机会卡在停机坪上？</h3><p>联邦航空管理局前高级管理人员、佛罗里达州安柏里德尔航空大学助理教授迈克尔·麦考密克表示，阻碍飞机起飞的天气是地面延误的主要原因之一。</p><p>由于空中交通管制员正在努力减少恶劣天气地区的拥堵，因此距离风暴系统数百英里的乘客可能会遇到地面延误。麦考密克说，严重且频繁的雷暴切断了飞机的航线。当航班无法起飞时，没有足够的登机口供抵达的飞机停放。人员配备或机械问题也可能导致延误。</p><p>纽约机场有限的跑道容量加剧了天气和空中交通管制问题</p>保罗·哈德森 (Paul Hudson)，消费者权益保护组织 FlyersRights 的总裁。<p></p><p>港务局表示，正在对其机场进行投资，包括机场滑行道，以帮助飞机更快地进出跑道。</p><h3>我的航空公司是否因停机坪延误而欠我赔偿？</h3><p>不可以。但他们必须在停机坪延误开始后两小时内为您提供零食和水。即使延误持续很长时间，他们也不需要提供餐点。</p><div class="media-object scope-web
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4>分享你的意见</h4><p><em>今年夏天您的航空旅行经历如何？加入下面的对话。</em></p></div></div><p>航空公司必须为可能需要的人提供工作厕所、舒适的机舱温度和医疗护理。没有定义为舒适的设定温度。</p><p>如果您的航班在停机坪延误后延误或取消，您可能需要赔偿。一些航空公司会为因延误或取消而导致的食品、酒店或地面交通提供代金券——只要延误或取消是在他们的控制范围内。 （与天气相关的问题不适用。）</p><h3>航空公司可以让乘客在飞机上停留多长时间？</h3><p>对于国内航班，交通部规则要求航空公司在延误超过三小时之前开始转移到乘客可以离开的地方。这适用于抵达和出发。对于国际航班，时间限制为四个小时。但出于安全、安保和空中交通管制相关原因，它允许例外。</p><p>麦考密克说，例如，如果您的飞机在 30 架飞机的队列中排名第四，那么脱离队列并返回登机口可能会被视为对空中交通运营的干扰。</p><h3>如果我的飞机被困在停机坪上该怎么办？</h3><p>在您有机会下飞机之前，您的选择是有限的。如果您选择在停机坪延误期间下机，航空公司不需要让您重新登机，您可能需要寻找其他航班。</p><p>麦考密克说，无法保证您下飞机后会与行李重聚。</p><p>哈德森说，这些天飞机已经满员，这意味着无法保证您能搭乘下一班航班。</p><p><em>这篇文章可能会更新</em>。</p><p><em>订阅新的</em> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/newsletters?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none"><em>《华尔街日报》旅游通讯，</em></a><em>了解《华尔街日报》旅游团队的更多提示和见解。</em></p><p>写信给 Allison Pohle，邮箱为<a href="mailto:allison.pohle@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">allison.pohle@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 25 Jul 2023 16:13:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/tarmac-delay-rights-airports-9c5b1464</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/tarmac-delay-rights-airports-9c5b1464<author><![CDATA[Allison Pohle]]></author><category> WSJ生活工作</category><category>航空公司</category><category>客运航空公司</category><category>机场</category><category>航空运输</category><category>运输/物流</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>运输</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>联合航空控股</category><category>伦敦大学艺术学院</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>运输</category><category>航空公司</category><category>客运航空公司</category><category>机场</category><category>航空运输</category><category>运输</category><category>后勤</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[At Spotify, Podcast Cuts and Higher Music Royalties Deepen Losses]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>流媒体巨头图书用户增长创下有史以来最强劲的季度<!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001081300"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="572" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-822523?width=860&amp;height=572" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> 6 月，喷火战机乐队 (Foo Fighters) 的戴夫·格罗尔 (Dave Grohl) 在 Spotify 在法国戛纳举办的活动中表演。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：安东尼·琼斯/盖蒂图片社</p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001081300"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者： <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/anne-steele" itemprop="url" rel="author">安妮·斯蒂尔</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">更新于 2023 年 7 月 25 日上午 11:07（东部时间） </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/spotify-spot-q2-earnings-report-2023-646fa771"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p> Generation Z and overseas listeners helped <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/SPOT" class="company-name">Spotify</a> notch its strongest ever quarter for new users, while the streaming giant reported steeper losses from podcasting cuts and higher music royalty costs.</p><p> The audio company is in the throes of an effort to improve profitability, which includes right-sizing its investments in podcasting and raising prices.</p><p> On Monday, Spotify said it <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/spotify-plans-to-raise-price-of-premium-plan-in-u-s-77c3f360?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">is raising prices for its premium subscription</a> to $10.99 a month in the US from its longstanding price of $9.99, confirming an earlier report by The Wall Street Journal. The company had told investors it would raise prices this year as part of a continuing push to consistently turn a profit.</p><p> Spotify shares fell 14.26% Tuesday after the company reported steeper losses from podcasting cuts and higher music royalty costs.</p><p> The Stockholm streaming giant notched its strongest-ever quarter for new users, yet missed its revenue target and offered a weaker-than-expected outlook for the current quarter.</p><p> The audio giant said it would soon raise prices in dozens of other markets around the world, including the UK, France, Mexico, Peru, Singapore and Hong Kong.</p><p> Asked about the company&#39;s ability to raise prices longer term, Chief Executive Daniel Ek said Spotify continues to improve its product, increase podcasting and expand its audiobooks offering. “If we&#39;re doing that, I believe that we have the ability to then raise prices to keep the value to price ratio at an appropriate level,” he said.</p><h3> How many new subscribers did Spotify add?</h3><ul class="articleList"><li> Overall, the streamer reported 551 million monthly active users, a 27% jump from a year earlier, 21 million ahead of guidance and a record high for the company. The company said it was helped by successful marketing and improved retention.</li><li> Spotify&#39;s base of paying subscribers—its most lucrative type of customer—rose 17% to 220 million, topping the company&#39;s expectations by three million.</li><li> User growth was stronger than expected in all regions, with particular strength in Latin America, the company said. The company also added more younger, Generation Z listeners. </li></ul><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=E91EB935-C3EE-42FF-B41A-246614F8F1A1&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fspotify-spot-q2-earnings-report-2023-646fa771&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption"> With 500 million monthly users, Spotify is the world&#39;s largest music streaming service. Here&#39;s an inside look at how the platform uses machine learning technology to generate personalized recommendations. Photo illustration: Ryan Trefes<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><h3>Is the company profitable?</h3><ul class="articleList"><li> The company posted a wider loss of €302 million, equivalent to about $335 million, or €1.55 a share, for the quarter ended in June, compared with €125 million, or 85 European cents, in the year-earlier period. Its gross margin fell to 24.1% as a result of €44 million in charges related to canceling podcast shows, staff layoffs and the impairment of excess real estate.</li></ul><ul class="articleList"><li> Spotify said it incurred higher music royalty costs in the period and saw some improvement in podcast profitability. It reached new licensing agreements with major-label partners after the quarter&#39;s end that, among other things, allowed the streamer to raise subscription prices. The company pays out about 70% of revenue to music rights holders.</li><li> Ek said in an interview that the new agreements and the company&#39;s price increases are a “win-win for Spotify and the music industry.”</li></ul><ul class="articleList"><li> For years, executives have said the company will give priority to investment in growth over profit as Spotify tried to attract users around the world and expand into new forms of audio. Last fall, the company indicated that profitability is expected to improve this year as it moves on from that period of heavy investment.</li></ul><ul class="articleList"><li> Free cash flow, a measure of the cash a company generates from operations that is viewed by many investors as a proxy for performance, was €9 million, compared with €37 million a year earlier and €57 million in the prior quarter. </li></ul><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="467" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-822533?width=700&amp;height=467" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Spotify is raising prices for its premium subscription to $10.99 a month in the US from $9.99.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Gabby Jones/Bloomberg News</p></figcaption></figure></div><h3> What about revenue?</h3><ul class="articleList"><li> Overall revenue for the second quarter was up 11% to €3.18 billion, shy of the company&#39;s forecast.</li><li> Subscriptions, the largest contributor to Spotify&#39;s top line, rose 11% to €2.77 billion. Revenue from advertising rose 12% to €404 million. Ad revenue has become increasingly important to the future of Spotify&#39;s podcast business and accounted for nearly 13% of its overall revenue during the second quarter.</li><li> Average revenue per user for the subscription business in the quarter slipped 6% to €4.27. That metric declined as a result of Spotify drawing new subscribers through discounted plans and lower prices in emerging markets.</li></ul><h3> How is its podcast business?</h3><ul class="articleList"><li> In June, Spotify said it <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/spotify-to-cut-200-jobs-as-it-reorganizes-podcasting-division-39720004?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">would cut about 200 jobs</a> , or 2% of its workforce, after struggling to make money in podcasting. The company has consolidated some of its premier Gimlet and Parcast studios and <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/meghan-markles-archetypes-podcast-at-spotify-wont-be-renewed-44311f4f?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">axed many of its original</a> shows.</li><li> Ek told investors Tuesday that the company made the “right bet” on podcasts four years ago before there was much data available on the market, and that Spotify is now the top platform for that format. As it cuts costs, “we&#39;re coming at this with the process of right-sizing some deals, doubling down on some of the things that worked really nicely and then stepping out of some deals and relationships that hasn&#39;t worked out,” he said.</li></ul><ul class="articleList"><li> Spotify also loosened exclusivity arrangements with some of its podcasts, and has begun distributing them to other platforms in a move aimed at increasing the audience and ad potential of those shows. Exclusive deals with its biggest stars, including Joe Rogan, Alex Cooper and Emma Chamberlain, remain in place.</li></ul><p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/NWSA" class="">News Corp</a> <span class="company-name-type">&#39;s</span> Dow Jones &amp; Co., publisher of The Wall Street Journal, has a content partnership with Spotify&#39;s Gimlet Media unit.</p><div class="media-object scope-web
          inline
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4>分享你的意见</h4><p><em>How much are you willing to pay for a premium music subscription?加入下面的对话。</em></p></div></div><p> Write to Anne Steele at <a href="mailto:anne.steele@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">anne.steele@wsj.com</a> </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
